<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Automated"><PMID Version="1">35100565</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2022</Year><Month>08</Month><Day>26</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2025</Year><Month>07</Month><Day>28</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Electronic-Print"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1555-0273</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>17</Volume><Issue>6</Issue><PubDate><Year>2022</Year><Month>Jun</Month><Day>01</Day></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>International journal of sports physiology and performance</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Int J Sports Physiol Perform</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>The Sleep Behaviors of Elite Australian Rules Footballers Before and After Games During an Entire Season.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>932</StartPage><EndPage>942</EndPage><MedlinePgn>932-942</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1123/ijspp.2021-0417</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText Label="PURPOSE" NlmCategory="OBJECTIVE">Most athletes sleep poorly around competition. The aim of this study was to examine sleep before/after games during an entire season in elite Australian Rules footballers (N = 37) from the same team.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="METHODS" NlmCategory="METHODS">Sleep was monitored using activity monitors for 4 consecutive nights (beginning 2 nights before games) during 19 rounds of a season. Differences in sleep on the nights before/after games, and differences in sleep before/after games as a function of game time (day vs evening), location (local vs interstate), and outcome (win vs loss), were examined using linear mixed effects models.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="RESULTS" NlmCategory="RESULTS">Players fell asleep earlier (+1.9&#xa0;h; P &lt; .001), and woke up later (+1&#xa0;h; P &lt; .001) on the night before games compared with the night of games. Players obtained less sleep on the night of games than on the night before games (5.2&#xa0;h vs 7.7&#xa0;h; P &lt; .001), and this reduction was exacerbated when games were played in the evening-after evening games, players obtained approximately 40 minutes less sleep than after day games (P &lt; .001). Sleep duration on the nights before and after games was not affected by game location or game outcome, but players had later sleep onset (P &lt; .001) and offset times (P &lt; .001) on most nights when sleeping away from home.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="CONCLUSIONS" NlmCategory="CONCLUSIONS">Elite footballers obtain good sleep on the night before games but obtain approximately 30% less sleep on the night of games. Given the role of sleep in recovery, it will be important to determine whether a reduction in sleep duration of this magnitude impairs recovery on the days following games.</AbstractText></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Sargent</LastName><ForeName>Charli</ForeName><Initials>C</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Rogalski</LastName><ForeName>Brent</ForeName><Initials>B</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Montero</LastName><ForeName>Ashley</ForeName><Initials>A</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Roach</LastName><ForeName>Gregory D</ForeName><Initials>GD</Initials></Author></AuthorList><Language>eng</Language><PublicationTypeList><PublicationType UI="D016428">Journal Article</PublicationType></PublicationTypeList><ArticleDate DateType="Electronic"><Year>2022</Year><Month>01</Month><Day>31</Day></ArticleDate></Article><MedlineJournalInfo><Country>United States</Country><MedlineTA>Int J Sports Physiol Perform</MedlineTA><NlmUniqueID>101276430</NlmUniqueID><ISSNLinking>1555-0265</ISSNLinking></MedlineJournalInfo><CitationSubset>IM</CitationSubset><MeshHeadingList><MeshHeading><DescriptorName UI="D056352" MajorTopicYN="Y">Athletes</DescriptorName></MeshHeading><MeshHeading><DescriptorName UI="D001315" MajorTopicYN="N" Type="Geographic">Australia</DescriptorName></